ce:section.ce:para:
The resulting fitting parameters, including the determined averaged lifetime (
τ
) are presented in Table 1 . The detection of the two distinct emission lifetimes (5.50 ± 0.12 and 13.89 ± 0.04 ns for O_300min with the detection at 450 nm) indicates the presence of two different emitting sites in the C-QD, presumably surface and cores sites. The short lifetime should be attributed to the surface sites, structural defects in nature that are inherently associated with faster radiative decays and are more susceptible to being effectively quenched by water molecules through vibrational coupling with the higher O − H vibrational overtones. The emission from the ordered interior sites is less vulnerable to the non-radiative quenching effects. In accordance with this, promoting the emission detection from bigger C-QDs, by changing the emission detection from 425 to 540 nm, results in the longer lifetime and corresponding relative amplitude systematically increasing, and the relative amplitude of the shorter lifetime significantly decreasing to half and one third for O300_min MW_15min suspensions, respectively.

Still, the coatings absorbance capacity and homogeneity are not the only preponderant factors. The absence of colour, as much as possible, is desired. As a result, the quantification of the colour gain in the glass substrate after the addition of the coating is extremely important and it was evaluated (Fig. 12
                     ). Fig. 12 data show that microwave-based coatings have higher ΔE, meaning they are darker and less desirable for the objective. MW samples have higher ΔE than the O samples because, as seen in Fig. 2 MW15min, the peak of absorbance is closer to the visible range than O300min, with a broader absorbance band. This results in more absorbance in the visible range even with MW samples being thinner than the oven samples (Fig. 8 
                     B and D).
